  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making large amounts of money generated by a criminal activity, such as drug trafficking or terrorist funding, appear to have come from a legitimate source. This is typically done by moving the funds through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nThe laws and penalties for money laundering can vary by country, but it is generally considered a serious offense. In the United States, for example, money laundering is a federal crime under the Bank Secrecy Act and the Money Laundering Control Act, with penalties that can include hefty fines and imprisonment.\n\nSimilarly, in the UK, the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 makes it a criminal offense to launder the proceeds of any crime. Convictions can result in prison sentences of up to 14 years and unlimited fines.\n\nInternational efforts to combat money laundering are coordinated by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and combating the financing of terrorism (CFT). Countries that are members of the FATF are expected to criminalize money laundering and related activities and to take measures to detect, prevent, and prosecute these crimes.",
